Note:
This file handles loop-invariant code motion (LICM) optimization.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Process loop-invariant code motion and loop optimization
- Handle invariant detection and invariant hoisting
- Manage loop optimization and loop transformation
- Process loop validation and loop verification

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Loop-invariant code motion improves loop performance by hoisting invariant computations
- Proper LICM handling ensures correct invariant identification and safe hoisting
- LICM support enables Runa compilation for optimized loop code generation

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Loop-invariant code motion and loop optimization
- Invariant detection and invariant hoisting
- Loop optimization and loop transformation
- Loop validation and loop verification
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: IMPORTS
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir_nodes.runa" as MIRNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/cfg.runa" as CFG
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/dominance.runa" as Dominance
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dictionary
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/ordered_map.runa" as OMap
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/set.runa" as Set
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE DEFINITIONS - Loop Information and LICM Context
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "LoopInfo":
    @Reasoning
    Represents a natural loop in the CFG.

    **NATURAL LOOP:**
    A natural loop is defined by a back edge (B → H) where:
    - H (header) dominates B (back-edge source)
    - Loop body = nodes that can reach B without going through H

    **MEMORY LAYOUT** (64 bytes):
    ```
    Offset 0:  header_id (Integer - loop header block ID)
    Offset 8:  preheader_id (Integer - preheader block ID, 0 if none)
    Offset 16: body_blocks (Integer - Set pointer to block IDs in loop)
    Offset 24: exit_blocks (Integer - Set pointer to exit block IDs)
    Offset 32: back_edges (Integer - List pointer to (source, target) pairs)
    Offset 40: nesting_level (Integer - 0 = outermost)
    Offset 48: parent_loop (Integer - parent LoopInfo pointer, 0 if outermost)
    Offset 56: invariant_count (Integer - number of invariant instructions)
    ```
    @End Reasoning

    header_id as Integer
    preheader_id as Integer
    body_blocks as Integer
    exit_blocks as Integer
    back_edges as Integer
    nesting_level as Integer
    parent_loop as Integer
    invariant_count as Integer
End Type

Type called "LICMContext":
    @Reasoning
    Context for Loop-Invariant Code Motion optimization.

    **LICM ALGORITHM:**
    1. Detect natural loops (back-edge identification)
    2. Insert preheaders so every loop has a single hoist landing pad
    3. Recompute dominance (preheaders change the topology)
    4. Detect loop-invariant instructions (fixed-point, per loop)
    5. Check hoisting safety (pure non-trapping whitelist, dominates exits)
    6. Hoist invariant instructions to the preheader in marking order

    **MEMORY LAYOUT** (96 bytes):
    ```
    Offset 0:  cfg (Integer - MIRCFG pointer)
    Offset 8:  loops (Integer - List of LoopInfo pointers)
    Offset 16: invariant_insts (Integer - Set of string-encoded invariant
               instruction pointers; recreated fresh for every loop)
    Offset 24: hoisted_count (Integer - number of instructions hoisted)
    Offset 32: loops_processed (Integer - number of loops processed)
    Offset 40: preheaders_inserted (Integer - number of preheaders created)
    Offset 48: dominance_ptr (Integer - DominanceInfo pointer, owned;
               recomputed after preheader insertion)
    Offset 56: function_ptr (Integer - MIRFunction pointer; value-id and
               instruction lookups are threaded through the function)
    Offset 64: def_map (Integer - OMap value_id -> defining instruction.
               LOCAL def-use structure built by one CFG scan: SSA does NOT
               materialize MIRValue use-lists (Wave 4 finding) and
               collections/dictionary string-hashes keys so integer keys
               crash (Wave 3 finding) - hence an integer-keyed ordered map)
    Offset 72: invariant_list (Integer - List of invariant instruction
               pointers in MARKING order; an instruction is only marked
               after every operand is invariant, so marking order is a
               valid dependency (topological) order for hoisting;
               recreated fresh for every loop)
    Offset 80: block_to_loop (Integer - Dictionary: block_id string -> LoopInfo)
    Offset 88: iteration_count (Integer - invariant detection iterations)
    ```
    @End Reasoning

    cfg as Integer
    loops as Integer
    invariant_insts as Integer
    hoisted_count as Integer
    loops_processed as Integer
    preheaders_inserted as Integer
    dominance_ptr as Integer
    function_ptr as Integer
    def_map as Integer
    invariant_list as Integer
    block_to_loop as Integer
    iteration_count as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONTEXT MANAGEMENT
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "build_def_map" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Builds the pass-local definition map: SSA value id -> defining
    instruction pointer. This is the LOCAL def-use structure that replaces
    the never-implemented SSA.build_def_use_chains dependency. Two prior
    findings shape it: SSA construction does not materialize MIRValue
    use-lists (Wave 4), so the only authoritative def source is the
    instruction stream itself; and collections/dictionary string-hashes
    its keys, so integer keys crash at runtime (Wave 3) — hence the
    integer-keyed ordered map. One O(I) scan up front converts every
    later "who defines this operand?" probe in the fixed-point invariant
    analysis into an O(1) omap_get, and a value id ABSENT from the map is
    by construction defined outside every block (a function parameter),
    which the invariance classifier treats as trivially loop-invariant.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Walks every block in the CFG's canonical storage list and every
    instruction in each block's instruction List. For every instruction
    whose header value_id (offset 8) is non-zero, records
    omap_set(def_map, value_id, instruction). Phi results participate
    because OD-1 mirrors the phi result into the header value_id slot.
    Returns the populated OMap; the caller owns it.
    @End Implementation

    Let def_map be proc omap_create from OMap
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return def_map
    End If

    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return def_map
    End If

    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks
    Let b_idx be 0
    While b_idx is less than block_count:
        Let block_ptr be proc get from List with blocks, b_idx
        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block_ptr
            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                Let i_idx be 0
                While i_idx is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with instructions, i_idx
                    If inst_ptr is not equal to 0:
                        Let value_id be proc get_mir_node_value_id from MIR with inst_ptr
                        If value_id is not equal to 0:
                            proc omap_set from OMap with def_map, value_id, inst_ptr
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set i_idx to i_idx plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set b_idx to b_idx plus 1
    End While

    Return def_map
End Process

Process called "create_licm_context" that takes function_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs the LICM analysis context that ties together the function
    under optimization with its CFG, the dominance tree, the local
    definition map, and the per-pass bookkeeping structures (loop list,
    invariant set/list, statistics counters). Every downstream LICM stage
    reads its inputs and writes its outputs through this single shared
    block, so the constructor is the only place where ownership of those
    auxiliary tables is established.

    The pass is keyed on the FUNCTION (not the bare CFG) because value-id
    bookkeeping — the definition map and value registration — lives on
    MIRFunction, and the CFG is derived via the canonical
    MIR.get_mir_function_cfg accessor.

    Dominance must be computed up front because back-edge identification
    and natural-loop body discovery require a ready dominance oracle.
    insert_preheaders RECOMPUTES it after mutating the topology; the
    context owns whichever instance is current and destroy_licm_context
    frees it.

    Returns the populated context pointer on success, or 0 if the
    function/CFG is null or any allocation fails.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocates the 96-byte context block via Layout.allocate and populates
    it field-by-field using the canonical offsets documented on LICMContext:
      0   cfg                  (MIR.get_mir_function_cfg(function))
      8   loops                (List, fresh)
      16  invariant_insts      (Set, fresh; recreated per loop)
      24  hoisted_count        (0)
      32  loops_processed      (0)
      40  preheaders_inserted  (0)
      48  dominance_ptr        (Dominance.compute_dominance_tree(cfg))
      56  function_ptr         (argument)
      64  def_map              (build_def_map(cfg) - integer-keyed OMap)
      72  invariant_list       (List, fresh; recreated per loop)
      80  block_to_loop        (Dictionary, fresh; string block-id keys)
      88  iteration_count      (0)
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Dominance computation dominates construction cost. The definition map
    scan is O(I) in the instruction count and pays for itself after the
    first fixed-point iteration of any non-trivial loop. The context
    itself is a flat 96-byte block.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If function_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "create_licm_context: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc get_mir_function_cfg from MIR with function_ptr
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "create_licm_context: function has no CFG"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate context (96 bytes)
    Let context_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 96
    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "create_licm_context: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set CFG
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0, cfg_ptr

    Note: Create loops list
    Let loops_list be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8, loops_list

    Note: Create invariant instructions set
    Let invariant_set be proc create from Set
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 16, invariant_set

    Note: Initialize counters to 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24, 0 Note: hoisted_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32, 0 Note: loops_processed
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40, 0 Note: preheaders_inserted

    Note: Compute dominance information
    Let dom_info be proc compute_dominance_tree from Dominance with cfg_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48, dom_info

    Note: Thread the function pointer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 56, function_ptr

    Note: Build the local definition map (value id -> defining instruction)
    Let def_map be proc build_def_map with cfg_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 64, def_map

    Note: Create the marking-order invariant list
    Let invariant_list be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72, invariant_list

    Note: Create block_to_loop mapping
    Let block_to_loop be proc create from Dictionary
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80, block_to_loop

    Note: Initialize iteration count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 88, 0

    Return context_ptr
End Process

Process called "destroy_licm_context" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Releases every byte allocated by create_licm_context plus all
    LoopInfo records and their owned body/exit/back-edge collections.
    LICM context lifetime is bounded by a single optimize_function_with_licm
    invocation, so the constructor and destructor are the only memory
    handoff points; making the destructor responsible for every nested
    structure keeps the call sites in optimize_function_with_licm
    leak-free even when error paths short-circuit the pass.

    The destructor must walk loops_list and dispose of each LoopInfo's
    Set/List children before destroying loops_list itself because the
    outer List.destroy only releases the array of pointers, not the
    objects they reference. The same constraint applies to invariant_insts
    (a Set of instruction pointers, but the instructions themselves are
    owned by MIR blocks and must not be freed) and block_to_loop (a
    Dictionary whose values alias LoopInfo entries already disposed in
    the loops_list walk, so the dictionary only releases its bucket
    storage).

    Returns 1 on success; returns 0 only when the context pointer is
    null. The destructor never raises — all child destroyers are
    null-tolerant.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Performs an ordered teardown:
      1. loops_list (offset 8): iterate every LoopInfo, free its
         body_blocks Set (offset 16), exit_blocks Set (offset 24), and
         back_edges List (offset 32) including the 16-byte edge pairs it
         owns, then deallocate the 64-byte LoopInfo struct. After the
         walk, destroy loops_list.
      2. invariant_insts (offset 16): destroy the Set. The pointed-to
         instructions remain owned by MIR.
      3. invariant_list (offset 72): destroy the List spine (same
         non-ownership rule).
      4. def_map (offset 64): omap_destroy. Values are borrowed
         instruction pointers.
      5. dominance_ptr (offset 48): destroy_dominance_info — the context
         OWNS the dominance info it computed (constructor and the
         insert_preheaders recompute both store the owned instance here).
      6. block_to_loop (offset 80): destroy the Dictionary. Values alias
         LoopInfo entries already freed in phase 1.
      7. Deallocate the 96-byte context block itself.
    @End Implementation

    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Free loops list and LoopInfo structures
    Let loops_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8
    If loops_list is not equal to 0:
        Let loop_count be proc length from List with loops_list
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than loop_count:
            Let loop_info be proc get from List with loops_list, i
            If loop_info is not equal to 0:
                Note: Free loop's body_blocks set
                Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16
                If body_blocks is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from Set with body_blocks
                End If

                Note: Free loop's exit_blocks set
                Let exit_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 24
                If exit_blocks is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from Set with exit_blocks
                End If

                Note: Free loop's back_edges list and the 16-byte edge
                Note: pairs it owns (transferred from find_back_edges)
                Let back_edges be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 32
                If back_edges is not equal to 0:
                    Let edge_count be proc length from List with back_edges
                    Let e_idx be 0
                    While e_idx is less than edge_count:
                        Let edge_pair be proc get from List with back_edges, e_idx
                        If edge_pair is not equal to 0:
                            proc deallocate from Layout with edge_pair
                        End If
                        Set e_idx to e_idx plus 1
                    End While
                    proc destroy from List with back_edges
                End If

                Note: Free LoopInfo structure
                proc deallocate from Layout with loop_info
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc destroy from List with loops_list
    End If

    Note: Free invariant_insts set
    Let invariant_set be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 16
    If invariant_set is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Set with invariant_set
    End If

    Note: Free invariant_list (List of borrowed instruction pointers)
    Let invariant_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72
    If invariant_list is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from List with invariant_list
    End If

    Note: Free the local definition map
    Let def_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 64
    If def_map is not equal to 0:
        proc omap_destroy from OMap with def_map
    End If

    Note: Free the owned dominance info
    Let dom_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48
    If dom_info is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy_dominance_info from Dominance with dom_info
    End If

    Note: Free block_to_loop dictionary
    Let block_to_loop be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80
    If block_to_loop is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dictionary with block_to_loop
    End If

    Note: Free context structure
    proc deallocate from Layout with context_ptr

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "print_licm_stats" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Prints LICM statistics.

    Returns 1 on success.
    @End Reasoning

    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Display ""
    Display "============================================"
    Display "LICM STATISTICS"
    Display "============================================"

    Let loops_processed be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32
    Let loops_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with loops_processed
    Display "Loops processed: " joined with loops_str

    Let preheaders_inserted be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40
    Let preheaders_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with preheaders_inserted
    Display "Preheaders inserted: " joined with preheaders_str

    Let hoisted_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24
    Let hoisted_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with hoisted_count
    Display "Instructions hoisted: " joined with hoisted_str

    Let iteration_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 88
    Let iter_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with iteration_count
    Display "Invariant detection iterations: " joined with iter_str

    Display "============================================"
    Display ""

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LOOP DETECTION - Natural Loop Identification
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_back_edge" that takes source_id as Integer, target_id as Integer, dominance_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tests whether the directed CFG edge (source -> target) is a back
    edge under the standard natural-loop definition: target must
    dominate source. This is the foundational predicate the rest of
    loop detection layers on top of — every natural loop in the CFG is
    identified by exactly one back edge, and the loop's header is the
    edge's target.

    Returns 1 when the edge is a back edge, 0 otherwise. A null
    dominance oracle is treated as "no back edges known" (returns 0)
    rather than raising, since the loop detector tolerates an empty
    back-edge set as a valid analysis result for a loop-free CFG.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegates the dominance test to Dominance.dominates(info, dom, blk)
    on the precomputed dominance tree (the canonical oracle; there is no
    does_dominate). The check walks the immediate-dominator chain.
    @End Implementation

    If dominance_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if target dominates source
    Let target_dominates be proc dominates from Dominance with dominance_ptr, target_id, source_id

    Return target_dominates
End Process

Process called "find_back_edges" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer, dominance_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Enumerates every back edge present in the CFG by visiting all
    (block, successor) edges and testing each one with is_back_edge.
    Back-edge discovery is the entry point of natural-loop detection:
    once back edges are known, each one generates exactly one
    LoopInfo, with the back edge's target serving as the loop header
    and its source as the seed for body discovery.

    The result list owns its (source, target) pair allocations and the
    caller is responsible for destroying it after extracting the edges
    into LoopInfo records (detect_natural_loops handles this transfer).

    Returns the populated List of edge-pair pointers on success, or 0
    when the CFG or dominance argument is null. An empty list (length 0)
    is a valid result meaning the CFG is reducible and loop-free.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Iterates every block POINTER in the canonical storage list
    (CFG.get_mir_cfg_blocks, borrowed). For each block B, iterates B's
    successor BLOCK IDS and applies is_back_edge(B, S, dominance).
    A back edge produces a 16-byte heap pair (source_id at offset 0,
    target_id at offset 8) appended to the result List.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cost is O(E) edge tests, each O(log N) via the dominance oracle, so
    total O(E log N). For typical CFGs (E ~ 3*N) this is the dominant
    cost of loop detection. The 16-byte pair allocation per back edge
    is the only heap traffic — pair count is bounded by the number of
    natural loops, which is at most N for a reducible CFG.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If dominance_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let back_edges be proc create from List

    Note: Get the block POINTER storage list (canonical accessor)
    Let all_blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    If all_blocks is equal to 0:
        Return back_edges
    End If

    Let block_count be proc length from List with all_blocks
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than block_count:
        Let block_ptr be proc get from List with all_blocks, i
        Let block_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from CFG with block_ptr

        Note: Successor lists hold BLOCK IDS (canonical representation)
        Let successors be proc get_block_successors from MIR with block_ptr
        If successors is not equal to 0:
            Let succ_count be proc length from List with successors
            Let j be 0

            While j is less than succ_count:
                Let succ_id be proc get from List with successors, j

                Note: Check if this is a back edge
                Let is_back be proc is_back_edge with block_id, succ_id, dominance_ptr

                If is_back is equal to 1:
                    Note: Create (source, target) pair (16 bytes)
                    Let edge_pair be proc allocate from Layout with 16
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with edge_pair, 0, block_id
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with edge_pair, 8, succ_id

                    proc append from List with back_edges, edge_pair
                End If

                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return back_edges
End Process

Process called "compute_loop_body" that takes header_id as Integer, back_edge_source as Integer, cfg_ptr as Integer, dominance_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the natural-loop body for back edge (back_edge_source -> header_id)
    as the set of CFG blocks that can reach back_edge_source without
    crossing header_id. This is the textbook natural-loop definition
    and the only block set safe to treat as "inside the loop" for
    every subsequent LICM stage (invariant detection, hoist safety,
    preheader insertion). The header is included by definition; the
    back-edge source is included as the worklist seed.

    The result Set holds raw integer block IDs. The Set primitive
    string-encodes its keys INTERNALLY (collections/set add/contains
    take the integer element), so callers must never pre-encode —
    doing so would key the set on string pointer values and break
    every membership check.

    Returns the populated body Set on success, or 0 when the CFG
    argument is null. The header_id is unconditionally included even
    if the body would otherwise be empty (degenerate self-loop), so
    every natural loop has at least one body block.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Classic reverse-reachability worklist:
      1. Seed body = {back_edge_source, header_id}.
      2. worklist = [back_edge_source].
      3. While worklist non-empty: pop current_id, fetch its block via
         get_block_by_id, iterate predecessors. For each predecessor P
         that is not header_id and not already in body, add P to body
         and push it onto the worklist.
    The header_id check at step 3 is what bounds the search — the loop
    body terminates upward at the header because the header dominates
    every body block by definition of "natural".

    Elements are raw integer block ids (the Set encodes internally).
    The worklist is destroyed before return; body_blocks is handed to
    the caller.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(|body|) Set inserts and O(|edges-into-body|) predecessor walks,
    each predecessor walk being O(in-degree). Total: O(N + E) for a
    typical loop body where N is body size. Integer-to-string
    conversion is O(log block_id) per insertion; for CFGs with up to
    ~10^6 blocks this is bounded by ~7 bytes per encoded key.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let body_blocks be proc create from Set
    Let worklist be proc create from List

    Note: Add back-edge source and header to body. The Set primitive
    Note: takes RAW INTEGER elements (it string-encodes its keys
    Note: internally) - pre-encoding here would key the set on string
    Note: POINTER values and break membership tests.
    proc add from Set with body_blocks, back_edge_source
    proc add from Set with body_blocks, header_id

    Note: Add back-edge source to worklist
    proc append from List with worklist, back_edge_source

    Note: Process worklist
    While proc length from List with worklist is greater than 0:
        Note: Pop from worklist
        Let current_id be proc get from List with worklist, 0
        proc remove_at from List with worklist, 0

        Note: Get current block
        Let current_block be proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, current_id
        If current_block is not equal to 0:
            Note: Predecessor lists hold BLOCK IDS
            Let predecessors be proc get_block_predecessors from MIR with current_block
            If predecessors is not equal to 0:
                Let pred_count be proc length from List with predecessors
                Let i be 0

                While i is less than pred_count:
                    Let pred_id be proc get from List with predecessors, i

                    Note: Don't go past header
                    If pred_id is not equal to header_id:
                        Let already_in_body be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, pred_id

                        If already_in_body is equal to 0:
                            Note: Add to body and worklist
                            proc add from Set with body_blocks, pred_id
                            proc append from List with worklist, pred_id
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set i to i plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc destroy from List with worklist

    Return body_blocks
End Process

Process called "compute_loop_exits" that takes loop_info as Integer, cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Identifies every block that lies outside the loop but is the target
    of an edge originating inside the loop. These are the loop's exits,
    and their identification is load-bearing for hoist safety:
    can_hoist_instruction must establish that the candidate instruction
    dominates every loop exit, otherwise the hoist would change the
    program's observable behaviour on paths that take the exit before
    the original instruction would have executed.

    The exit set is keyed by string-encoded block ID to match the
    representation used for body_blocks, so cross-set lookups during
    invariant analysis use the same key format throughout.

    Returns the populated exit-block Set on success, or 0 if loop_info
    or cfg is null. An empty exit set means the loop is infinite under
    static analysis (no exits) and every invariant instruction in such
    a loop is automatically exit-dominating.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Iterates every block in loop_info.body_blocks. For each body block,
    walks its successors; any successor not already in body_blocks is
    an exit and is inserted (string-encoded) into the exit set.
    Successor pointer retrieval uses get_block_by_id keyed by the
    string-decoded body block id.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(|body| + |edges-out-of-body|) — bounded by O(E) over the loop's
    induced subgraph. The string encode/decode round-trip is the only
    non-pointer cost; for tight inner loops this is the warmest path
    in compute_loop_exits but remains negligible compared to dominance
    queries elsewhere in the pass.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let exit_blocks be proc create from Set
    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16

    Note: Enumerate body block ids (to_list returns a fresh List of raw
    Note: integer elements owned by the caller)
    Let body_members be proc to_list from Set with body_blocks
    Let body_count be proc length from List with body_members

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than body_count:
        Let block_id be proc get from List with body_members, i

        Let block_ptr be proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id
        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Note: Successor lists hold BLOCK IDS
            Let successors be proc get_block_successors from MIR with block_ptr
            If successors is not equal to 0:
                Let succ_count be proc length from List with successors
                Let j be 0

                While j is less than succ_count:
                    Let succ_id be proc get from List with successors, j

                    Note: If successor not in loop body, it's an exit
                    Let in_body be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, succ_id
                    If in_body is equal to 0:
                        proc add from Set with exit_blocks, succ_id
                    End If

                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy from List with body_members

    Return exit_blocks
End Process

Process called "detect_natural_loops" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Top-level loop-detection driver. Materialises one LoopInfo per back
    edge, populates each with its header, body, exit set, and back-edge
    list, and registers every body block in block_to_loop so later
    stages can answer "which loop contains this block?" in O(1).

    The current implementation treats each back edge as a distinct
    natural loop; merging back edges that share a header (multi-back-edge
    irreducible patterns are not produced by structured frontends but
    can arise after CFG simplification) is left to a later normalisation
    pass — the per-edge representation here is correct because LICM
    treats each LoopInfo independently and the union of their hoists
    is equivalent to a merged-loop hoist.

    Returns the number of loops detected. Zero is a valid result for
    loop-free functions and is handled by optimize_function_with_licm
    as an early termination.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Phases:
      1. Resolve cfg, dominance, loops_list, block_to_loop from context.
      2. find_back_edges -> back_edges list of (source, target) pairs.
      3. For each pair:
         a. Allocate a 64-byte LoopInfo and set header_id (offset 0),
            preheader_id=0 (offset 8), body_blocks via compute_loop_body
            (offset 16), exit_blocks via compute_loop_exits (offset 24),
            back_edges list seeded with this pair (offset 32),
            nesting_level=0/parent_loop=0/invariant_count=0
            (offsets 40/48/56 — to be filled in later phases).
         b. Append the LoopInfo to loops_list.
         c. For every block id in body_blocks, set
            block_to_loop[block_id] = loop_info.
      4. Destroy back_edges (LoopInfo retains its own pair pointer in
         the per-loop back_edges list).
    Returns loops_list length.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Dominates by find_back_edges cost (O(E log N)) plus the per-loop
    body computation (O(N + E) per loop). For nests of L loops with
    average body size B the total is O(L*B + E log N), which is the
    optimal complexity for natural-loop detection on a precomputed
    dominance tree.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let dominance_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48
    Let loops_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8
    Let block_to_loop be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80

    Note: Find all back edges
    Let back_edges be proc find_back_edges with cfg_ptr, dominance_ptr
    If back_edges is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let edge_count be proc length from List with back_edges

    Note: Create LoopInfo for each back edge
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than edge_count:
        Let edge_pair be proc get from List with back_edges, i
        Let source_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with edge_pair, 0
        Let target_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with edge_pair, 8

        Note: Allocate LoopInfo (64 bytes)
        Let loop_info be proc allocate from Layout with 64

        Note: Set header_id
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0, target_id

        Note: No preheader yet
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 8, 0

        Note: Compute loop body
        Let body_blocks be proc compute_loop_body with target_id, source_id, cfg_ptr, dominance_ptr
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16, body_blocks

        Note: Compute exit blocks
        Let exit_blocks be proc compute_loop_exits with loop_info, cfg_ptr
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 24, exit_blocks

        Note: Create back_edges list for this loop
        Let loop_back_edges be proc create from List
        proc append from List with loop_back_edges, edge_pair
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 32, loop_back_edges

        Note: Initialize nesting level and parent (will be computed later)
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 40, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 48, 0

        Note: Initialize invariant count
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 56, 0

        Note: Add to loops list
        proc append from List with loops_list, loop_info

        Note: Map all body blocks to this loop (Dictionary requires
        Note: STRING keys - string-hash on integer keys crashes)
        Let body_members be proc to_list from Set with body_blocks
        Let body_count be proc length from List with body_members
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than body_count:
            Let body_block_id be proc get from List with body_members, j
            Let block_id_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with body_block_id
            proc set from Dictionary with block_to_loop, block_id_str, loop_info
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from List with body_members

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Free the back_edges spine only - each pair pointer was
    Note: transferred into its LoopInfo's per-loop back_edges list,
    Note: which owns it from here (destroy_licm_context frees it)
    proc destroy from List with back_edges

    Let loop_count be proc length from List with loops_list

    Return loop_count
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PREHEADER INSERTION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "needs_preheader" that takes loop_info as Integer, cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Predicate that decides whether the loop requires a fresh preheader
    block before hoisting can proceed. A preheader is the unique block
    that flows into the loop header from outside the loop and serves
    as the single landing pad for hoisted invariant instructions.

    Conditions:
      - If the header has multiple non-back-edge predecessors, the
        loop has multiple external entry points; we cannot place
        hoisted code on every such edge without code duplication, so
        a synthetic preheader is required.
      - Even with a single external predecessor, a dedicated preheader
        is preferred so that hoists never alter the layout or
        contents of the original predecessor block — preserving
        debug locations and avoiding cross-pass interference with
        other optimizations that may have settled the predecessor.

    Because both branches return 1 under the current LICM policy, this
    predicate currently always recommends preheader insertion when the
    header has any predecessor at all. The branching structure is
    retained as documentation of the analytical justification.

    Returns 1 if a preheader should be created, 0 if loop_info or cfg
    is null or the header has no predecessors at all (anomalous).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads header_id from loop_info offset 0 and body_blocks from
    offset 16. Resolves the header block via get_block_by_id, then
    counts predecessors not in body_blocks (these are external entries).
    Returns 1 in every well-formed case to enforce the
    "always preheader for hoisting" policy described above.
    @End Implementation

    If loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let header_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0
    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16

    Note: Get header block
    Let header_block be proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, header_id
    If header_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Count non-back-edge predecessors (predecessor lists hold IDS)
    Let predecessors be proc get_block_predecessors from MIR with header_block
    If predecessors is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pred_count be proc length from List with predecessors
    Let non_back_edge_preds be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than pred_count:
        Let pred_id be proc get from List with predecessors, i

        Note: Check if predecessor is in loop body (back edge)
        Let in_body be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, pred_id
        If in_body is equal to 0:
            Note: Non-back-edge predecessor
            Set non_back_edge_preds to non_back_edge_preds plus 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Need preheader if multiple external entries
    If non_back_edge_preds is greater than 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Also useful to have preheader for single entry for hoisting
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "insert_preheader" that takes loop_info as Integer, cfg_ptr as Integer, function_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Materialises a preheader block for the loop and rewires every
    external predecessor of the header to land in the preheader
    instead. After this transformation:
      - The preheader has exactly one successor: the loop header.
      - The header has exactly two predecessor categories: the
        preheader (from outside the loop) and back-edge sources
        (from inside the loop).
      - Every hoisted invariant instruction can be inserted at the
        end of the preheader (before its terminating branch) and is
        guaranteed to dominate every body block.

    Preheader insertion is the prerequisite for any subsequent hoist.
    The single-landing-pad property is what allows can_hoist_instruction
    to reason about exit dominance using the original instruction's
    block — once hoisted, the instruction's new "block" is the
    preheader, which by construction dominates the header and every
    block dominated by the header (i.e. the loop body).

    Returns the new preheader block ID, or 0 if loop_info or cfg is
    null, the header cannot be resolved, or block creation fails.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Create a fresh basic block via CFG.create_basic_block (returns the
       block POINTER), publish it via CFG.add_block_to_function, and read
       its id via CFG.get_mir_basic_block_id.
    2. Materialise the preheader terminator: an unconditional
       MIRNodes.create_mir_jump targeting the header block id (a MIRJump
       carries its target as a BLOCK ID at ext offset 72), appended via
       the canonical CFG.add_instruction_to_block.
    3. For every predecessor P of the header (predecessor lists hold
       BLOCK IDS): if P is NOT in body_blocks (i.e. P is an external
       entry, not a back edge), redirect the edge P -> header to
       P -> preheader by composing the canonical primitives:
         CFG.remove_cfg_edge(cfg, P, header)
         MIR.add_cfg_edge(cfg, P, preheader)
         CFG.update_terminator_target(cfg, P, header, preheader)
       (there is no redirect_edge in the canonical surface).
       Back-edge predecessors are deliberately left pointing at the
       header. The predecessor list is snapshotted before the walk
       because remove_cfg_edge mutates it.
    4. Header phi maintenance: for each phi in the header, every
       incoming whose block is a redirected external predecessor must
       now flow through the preheader. With exactly one external
       incoming the pair's block id is rewritten in place. With
       multiple external incomings a MERGE PHI is materialised in the
       preheader (fresh value id from the function), the external
       pairs are collapsed out of the header phi's pair list, and one
       (preheader, merge-phi) incoming replaces them — the only
       semantics-preserving rewrite when the external values differ.
    5. Add the preheader -> header CFG edge.
    6. Write the new preheader id into loop_info offset 8.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(P) where P is the number of header predecessors. Edge redirection
    is O(1) per edge through the CFG's adjacency representation.
    Preheader insertion runs once per loop and is dwarfed by the
    fixed-point invariant analysis later in the pass.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Preheader insertion mutates the CFG topology. It must run before
    any concurrent reader of the CFG (e.g. another optimization pass
    iterating predecessors) — the pass manager enforces single-writer
    discipline by serialising LICM with respect to other CFG-mutating
    passes. The preheader's terminating branch is the only instruction
    materialised here; no user-visible control-flow change occurs
    because the rewired predecessors still funnel into the header
    through the preheader.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let header_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0
    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16

    Note: Create and publish the preheader block (pointer, then id)
    Let preheader_block be proc create_basic_block from CFG with cfg_ptr
    If preheader_block is equal to 0:
        Display "insert_preheader: failed to create preheader block"
        Return 0
    End If
    proc add_block_to_function from CFG with cfg_ptr, preheader_block
    Let preheader_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from CFG with preheader_block

    Let header_block be proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, header_id
    If header_block is equal to 0:
        Display "insert_preheader: failed to get header block"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Terminate the preheader with an unconditional jump to the header
    Let jump_inst be proc create_mir_jump from MIRNodes with header_id
    proc add_instruction_to_block from CFG with preheader_block, jump_inst

    Note: Snapshot the external (non-back-edge) predecessors first -
    Note: remove_cfg_edge mutates the predecessor list being walked.
    Note: Predecessor lists hold BLOCK IDS.
    Let external_preds be proc create from List
    Let predecessors be proc get_block_predecessors from MIR with header_block
    If predecessors is not equal to 0:
        Let pred_count be proc length from List with predecessors
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than pred_count:
            Let pred_id be proc get from List with predecessors, i

            Note: A predecessor outside the loop body is an external entry
            Let in_body be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, pred_id
            If in_body is equal to 0:
                proc append from List with external_preds, pred_id
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Redirect every external edge pred -> header to pred -> preheader
    Note: (canonical composition; there is no redirect_edge primitive)
    Let ext_count be proc length from List with external_preds
    Let e_idx be 0
    While e_idx is less than ext_count:
        Let ext_pred_id be proc get from List with external_preds, e_idx
        proc remove_cfg_edge from CFG with cfg_ptr, ext_pred_id, header_id
        proc add_cfg_edge from MIR with cfg_ptr, ext_pred_id, preheader_id
        proc update_terminator_target from CFG with cfg_ptr, ext_pred_id, header_id, preheader_id
        Set e_idx to e_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Header phi maintenance. Every header phi incoming arriving from
    Note: a redirected external predecessor now flows through the
    Note: preheader. Pairs are stored flat: block at 2N, value at 2N+1.
    If ext_count is greater than 0:
        Let header_insts be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with header_block
        If header_insts is not equal to 0:
            Let header_inst_count be proc length from List with header_insts
            Let h_idx be 0
            While h_idx is less than header_inst_count:
                Let header_inst be proc get from List with header_insts, h_idx
                If header_inst is not equal to 0:
                    Let h_opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with header_inst
                    If h_opcode is equal to 20300:
                        proc reroute_phi_externals_through_preheader with header_inst, external_preds, preheader_block, preheader_id, function_ptr
                    End If
                End If
                Set h_idx to h_idx plus 1
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc destroy from List with external_preds

    Note: Wire the preheader -> header edge
    proc add_cfg_edge from MIR with cfg_ptr, preheader_id, header_id

    Note: Update loop info with preheader ID
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 8, preheader_id

    Return preheader_id
End Process

Process called "reroute_phi_externals_through_preheader" that takes phi_ptr as Integer, external_preds as Integer, preheader_block as Integer, preheader_id as Integer, function_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Maintains a single header phi across preheader insertion. Incomings
    from redirected external predecessors can no longer name those
    predecessors (the CFG edge now runs through the preheader). One
    external incoming is a pure rename. Multiple external incomings with
    potentially different values require a MERGE PHI in the preheader:
    the preheader is the unique join of the external entries, so merging
    there and feeding the single merged value into the header phi is the
    only rewrite that preserves the phi's per-path semantics.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Collect the pair-list indices whose incoming BLOCK is a member of
       external_preds.
    2. Zero matches: nothing to do.
    3. One match: rewrite the pair's block slot (index 2N) to
       preheader_id in place.
    4. Two or more: allocate a fresh value id on the function, create a
       MIRNodes.create_mir_phi_node in the preheader, move each external
       (block, value) pair onto it via add_phi_incoming, register the
       result in the function's value map and the preheader's phi
       registry (offset 88), insert it at the preheader's block START
       (before the jump terminator) via MIR.insert_instruction_at_block
       _start, then rebuild the header phi's pair list without the
       external pairs and append the single (preheader_id, merge value)
       incoming, re-syncing incoming_count at ext offset 88.
    @End Implementation

    If phi_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If external_preds is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pairs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 80
    If pairs is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pair_len be proc length from List with pairs
    Let ext_count be proc length from List with external_preds

    Note: Count external incomings and remember the first match index
    Let match_count be 0
    Let first_match_idx be 0 minus 1
    Let p_idx be 0
    While p_idx is less than pair_len:
        Let inc_block be proc get from List with pairs, p_idx
        Let is_external be 0
        Let x_idx be 0
        While x_idx is less than ext_count:
            Let ext_id be proc get from List with external_preds, x_idx
            If inc_block is equal to ext_id:
                Set is_external to 1
            End If
            Set x_idx to x_idx plus 1
        End While
        If is_external is equal to 1:
            Set match_count to match_count plus 1
            If first_match_idx is less than 0:
                Set first_match_idx to p_idx
            End If
        End If
        Set p_idx to p_idx plus 2
    End While

    If match_count is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    If match_count is equal to 1:
        Note: Pure rename: the external incoming now arrives via the preheader
        proc set from List with pairs, first_match_idx, preheader_id
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Multiple external incomings: materialise a preheader merge phi
    Let phi_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 96
    Let merge_vid be proc allocate_value_id from MIR with function_ptr
    Let merge_phi be proc create_mir_phi_node from MIRNodes with merge_vid, phi_type, preheader_block
    If merge_phi is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Rebuild the header phi pair list, moving external pairs onto
    Note: the merge phi
    Let rebuilt_pairs be proc create from List
    Set p_idx to 0
    While p_idx is less than pair_len:
        Let scan_block be proc get from List with pairs, p_idx
        Let scan_value be proc get from List with pairs, (p_idx plus 1)
        Let scan_external be 0
        Let s_idx be 0
        While s_idx is less than ext_count:
            Let scan_ext_id be proc get from List with external_preds, s_idx
            If scan_block is equal to scan_ext_id:
                Set scan_external to 1
            End If
            Set s_idx to s_idx plus 1
        End While
        If scan_external is equal to 1:
            proc add_phi_incoming from MIRNodes with merge_phi, scan_block, scan_value
        Otherwise:
            proc append from List with rebuilt_pairs, scan_block
            proc append from List with rebuilt_pairs, scan_value
        End If
        Set p_idx to p_idx plus 2
    End While

    Note: The merged value enters the header phi from the preheader
    proc append from List with rebuilt_pairs, preheader_id
    proc append from List with rebuilt_pairs, merge_vid

    Note: Swap the rebuilt pair list in and re-sync incoming_count
    proc destroy from List with pairs
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 80, rebuilt_pairs
    Let rebuilt_len be proc length from List with rebuilt_pairs
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 88, (rebuilt_len divided by 2)

    Note: Publish the merge phi: block start (before the jump terminator),
    Note: phi registry, and the function value map
    proc insert_instruction_at_block_start from MIR with preheader_block, merge_phi
    Let phi_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with preheader_block, 88
    If phi_registry is not equal to 0:
        proc append from List with phi_registry, merge_phi
    End If
    proc register_value_definition from MIR with function_ptr, merge_vid, merge_phi

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "insert_preheaders" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Walks every detected loop and inserts a preheader where
    needs_preheader recommends one. This is the second LICM stage,
    after detect_natural_loops and before mark_invariant_instructions.
    Running preheader insertion first means the invariant analysis
    can treat the preheader as the canonical hoist target without
    needing to re-check whether one exists.

    Returns the number of preheaders successfully created. The
    context's preheaders_inserted counter (offset 40) is updated to
    match for statistics reporting.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads cfg, function, and loops_list from the context. For each
    LoopInfo:
      - Calls needs_preheader to decide.
      - On 1, calls insert_preheader; counts successful insertions
        (return != 0).
    After the walk, when any preheader was inserted the CFG topology has
    changed, so the context's dominance info is RECOMPUTED (the old
    instance is destroyed, the fresh one stored at offset 48) — the
    hoist-safety dominance queries in can_hoist_instruction must run
    against the post-preheader graph. Writes the running total into
    context offset 40 before returning.
    @End Implementation

    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let function_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 56
    Let loops_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8

    Let loop_count be proc length from List with loops_list
    Let preheaders_created be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than loop_count:
        Let loop_info be proc get from List with loops_list, i

        Note: Check if preheader needed
        Let needs_ph be proc needs_preheader with loop_info, cfg_ptr

        If needs_ph is equal to 1:
            Let preheader_id be proc insert_preheader with loop_info, cfg_ptr, function_ptr
            If preheader_id is not equal to 0:
                Set preheaders_created to preheaders_created plus 1
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Preheaders changed the topology - recompute owned dominance
    If preheaders_created is greater than 0:
        Let old_dom be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48
        If old_dom is not equal to 0:
            proc destroy_dominance_info from Dominance with old_dom
        End If
        Let new_dom be proc compute_dominance_tree from Dominance with cfg_ptr
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48, new_dom
    End If

    Note: Update context counter
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40, preheaders_created

    Return preheaders_created
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INVARIANT DETECTION - Fixed-Point Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "get_instruction_block_id" that takes inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the id of the block an instruction currently resides in, or
    -1 when the instruction is detached (parent_block of 0). Derived
    from the canonical MIRNode parent_block back-pointer at header
    offset 56, which every canonical insertion path stamps
    (mir.runa add_instruction_to_block and
    insert_instruction_at_block_start, cfg.runa add_instruction_to_block)
    and the canonical remove_instruction_from_block clears. -1 (not 0)
    is the sentinel because 0 is the entry block's VALID id.
    @End Reasoning

    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Let parent_block be proc get_mir_node_parent_block from MIR with inst_ptr
    If parent_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Return proc get_mir_basic_block_id from CFG with parent_block
End Process

Process called "is_loop_invariant_operand" that takes operand_id as Integer, loop_info as Integer, invariant_set as Integer, def_map as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Per-operand classifier for the fixed-point invariant analysis. An
    operand is loop-invariant if, on every iteration of the loop, it
    has the same value. Sources of invariance, checked in order of
    decreasing cheapness:
      1. The operand has no entry in the definition map — it is not
         defined by any instruction in any block, i.e. it is a function
         parameter. Parameters are fixed for the whole invocation and
         therefore invariant in every loop.
      2. The operand's defining instruction is a MIR_CONST (20001) —
         constants are invariant by construction.
      3. The defining instruction lives in a block outside the loop
         body — such defs cannot be re-evaluated from inside the loop
         and are stable across iterations.
      4. The defining instruction has already been classified invariant
         in a previous step of the fixed-point loop (membership of the
         DEFINING INSTRUCTION pointer in invariant_set — the set is
         keyed by instruction pointer, matching what
         mark_invariant_instructions inserts; the pre-reconciliation
         code probed it with the operand VALUE id, a key family that was
         never inserted, so invariant chaining silently never fired).

    This classification is monotone: once an operand is classified
    invariant the classification cannot regress, so the fixed point
    converges.

    Returns 1 if invariant, 0 if not invariant or loop_info is null.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Probes the integer-keyed def_map (OMap) once. Absence => case 1.
    Otherwise reads the defining instruction's opcode (case 2), its
    residence block id via get_instruction_block_id against the loop's
    body_blocks Set (case 3), and finally the instruction-pointer key
    against invariant_set (case 4).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One O(1) omap probe plus at most one Set probe per call. The
    integer_to_string encodes are bounded by pointer/id digit counts.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16

    Note: Case 1 - no defining instruction anywhere: function parameter
    Let has_def be proc omap_contains from OMap with def_map, operand_id
    If has_def is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let defining_inst be proc omap_get from OMap with def_map, operand_id
    If defining_inst is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Case 2 - constants are invariant by construction
    Let def_opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with defining_inst
    If def_opcode is equal to 20001:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Case 3 - defined outside the loop body (Set elements are raw
    Note: integer block ids)
    Let defining_block_id be proc get_instruction_block_id with defining_inst
    If defining_block_id is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let is_in_loop be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, defining_block_id
        If is_in_loop is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Case 4 - defining instruction already classified invariant
    Note: (set elements are raw INSTRUCTION POINTERS)
    Let def_marked be proc contains from Set with invariant_set, defining_inst
    If def_marked is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "can_hoist_instruction" that takes inst_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, dominance_ptr as Integer, cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The hoist-safety predicate. This is the single proof obligation
    every LICM transformation must satisfy: hoisting must preserve
    program semantics in every possible execution.

    LICM is only sound when the candidate instruction satisfies a
    conjunction of three safety properties, each rejecting a distinct
    class of unsoundness:

    PROPERTY 1 — NO OBSERVABLE SIDE EFFECTS
    The instruction must be free of any effect a program could
    distinguish if it occurred in a different control-flow context.
    Hoisting from inside a loop to a preheader causes the instruction
    to execute on paths that originally bypassed it (in particular
    paths that would have exited the loop before the original
    instruction ran). Effects that would become visible on such paths
    are forbidden:
      - MIR_STORE writes to memory the program may observe later;
        hoisting can introduce spurious writes on early-exit paths
        and (worse) reorder writes relative to other memory
        operations. REJECT.
      - MIR_CALL may have arbitrary effects (I/O, memory, throwing).
        Hoisting may cause the call to execute when it would not
        have, or to execute fewer times than the original program
        would (which is itself observable for, e.g., counting side
        effects). REJECT.
      - MIR_LOAD is conservatively rejected even though it has no
        write effect, because a load can trap (null deref, segfault,
        unmapped page). The original program may have guarded the
        load with a branch that decided not to enter the loop body
        on the offending iteration; hoisting moves the load above
        that guard and would synthesize a trap on paths that did not
        originally exhibit one. A future enhancement may allow
        provably-safe loads (e.g. loads of identified-non-aliasing
        constants from unique-aliased base pointers known to be
        non-null and in-bounds), but the safe default is REJECT.
      - Implicit: divisions or other potentially-trapping ALU ops
        require the same treatment; the current opcode whitelist
        admits only side-effect-free, trap-free instructions, so they
        fall through to the dominance check below.

    PROPERTY 2 — DOMINATES ALL LOOP EXITS
    The instruction must execute on every path that exits the loop.
    Equivalently: the instruction's block must dominate every loop
    exit block. If the instruction does NOT dominate an exit E, then
    there is a path from the loop header to E that bypasses the
    instruction. On that path the program would not have evaluated
    the instruction; hoisting forces evaluation in the preheader,
    which precedes every loop iteration including the one that takes
    the bypass path. For a pure instruction this would still be
    semantics-preserving (the value is computed but unused on the
    bypass), but combined with Property 1 the strict dominance
    requirement guards future relaxations and matches the textbook
    LICM safety criterion. The check uses the precomputed dominance
    oracle (Dominance.dominates).

    PROPERTY 3 — MAY-NOT-THROW
    Combined with Property 1's rejection of MIR_CALL and MIR_LOAD,
    Property 3 is satisfied by construction for the surviving opcode
    set (arithmetic, logical, compare, move, constant). Any future
    opcode added to the whitelist must be re-audited against this
    property: hoisting an exception-throwing instruction would
    materialise the exception in the preheader, before the loop
    iteration that would have raised it would have executed,
    violating happens-before with respect to any other instructions
    in the iteration's prefix.

    All three properties must hold simultaneously. The conjunction is
    short-circuited: side-effect rejection returns 0 immediately so
    the dominance walk is skipped for the common case of obviously
    unsafe instructions.

    Returns 1 if all three properties hold and the hoist is safe,
    0 otherwise. Null inst_ptr or loop_info short-circuits to 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Steps:
      1. Read opcode via MIR.get_mir_node_opcode and test it against a
         POSITIVE whitelist of side-effect-free, trap-free,
         non-control-flow opcodes:
           20001 CONST; 20002-20004 ADD/SUB/MUL; 20007 NEG; 20008 COPY;
           20010-20016 bitwise/shift; 20100-20105 comparisons;
           20400-20408 casts.
         Everything else is rejected: stores/loads/field ops/deref
         (Property 1: memory effects or trap potential), calls/invokes/
         atomics (arbitrary effects), DIV/MOD 20005/20006 (divide-by-
         zero trap — Property 3; a path inside the loop may guard the
         divisor, and a preheader evaluation would trap on inputs the
         original program handled), terminators and phis (control flow
         and merge semantics are position-dependent by definition), and
         the debug/vector/exception bands. A whitelist fails CLOSED for
         any future opcode until it is audited against all three
         properties.
      2. Read exit_blocks (offset 24) and enumerate its members via
         Set.to_list. If dominance_ptr is non-null and there is at
         least one exit, query Dominance.dominates(dominance_ptr,
         inst_block_id, exit_block_id) for each exit. Any failure
         returns 0 (Property 2).
      3. Reaching the end means all three properties hold; return 1.
    inst_block_id is fetched once via the parent_block-derived
    get_instruction_block_id before the loop to avoid repeated lookups
    inside the exit walk; a detached instruction (-1) is rejected.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Per-call cost: one opcode read (O(1)), one block-id read (O(1)),
    one dominance query per exit (O(log N) average). For tight loops
    with a single exit (most natural loops) this is effectively a
    constant-time predicate. The exit walk is the inner loop of the
    fixed-point analysis when many candidates pass Property 1; the
    Set.to_list allocation per call is the main optimisation target
    if profiling identifies a hotspot.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    This predicate is the entire correctness boundary of the LICM
    pass. Any future relaxation (e.g. admitting safe loads, admitting
    speculatable calls) MUST update this predicate, not bypass it.
    The opcode whitelist is intentionally conservative: false
    negatives leave optimisation on the table but never produce
    incorrect code. False positives would silently corrupt program
    semantics on any non-trivial input. Every line of this routine is
    therefore part of Runa's compiler trust boundary.
    @End Security_Scope

    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

    Note: Positive whitelist (Properties 1 and 3) - fail closed
    Let hoistable_opcode be 0
    If opcode is equal to 20001:
        Set hoistable_opcode to 1
    End If
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20002 and opcode is less than or equal to 20004:
        Set hoistable_opcode to 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20007 or opcode is equal to 20008:
        Set hoistable_opcode to 1
    End If
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20010 and opcode is less than or equal to 20016:
        Set hoistable_opcode to 1
    End If
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20100 and opcode is less than or equal to 20105:
        Set hoistable_opcode to 1
    End If
    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20400 and opcode is less than or equal to 20408:
        Set hoistable_opcode to 1
    End If

    If hoistable_opcode is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check dominance of all loop exits (to_list returns a fresh
    Note: List of raw integer block ids owned by this caller)
    Let exit_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 24
    Let exit_members be proc to_list from Set with exit_blocks
    Let exit_count be proc length from List with exit_members

    Note: Instruction must dominate ALL loop exits to be safe to hoist
    If dominance_ptr is not equal to 0 and exit_count is greater than 0:
        Let inst_block_id be proc get_instruction_block_id with inst_ptr
        If inst_block_id is less than 0:
            Note: Detached instruction - no residence, no proof
            proc destroy from List with exit_members
            Return 0
        End If
        Let exit_idx be 0

        While exit_idx is less than exit_count:
            Let exit_block_id be proc get from List with exit_members, exit_idx

            Note: Check if instruction's block dominates this exit
            Let inst_dominates_exit be proc dominates from Dominance with dominance_ptr, inst_block_id, exit_block_id
            If inst_dominates_exit is equal to 0:
                Note: Instruction does not dominate this exit - unsafe to hoist
                proc destroy from List with exit_members
                Return 0
            End If

            Set exit_idx to exit_idx plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc destroy from List with exit_members

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mark_invariant_instructions" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Identifies the set of loop-invariant instructions using monotone
    fixed-point iteration over the loop's body. An instruction is
    classified invariant when every one of its operands is invariant
    AND can_hoist_instruction accepts it as safe to move. The set is
    seeded as empty and grows on each iteration; the analysis
    terminates when an iteration produces no new classifications,
    which is guaranteed to happen because the underlying lattice is
    finite (the body has finitely many instructions) and the
    classification function is monotone (an instruction once
    classified invariant never reverts).

    Coupling invariance discovery to the hoist-safety check inside
    the fixed-point body is deliberate: instructions that are
    invariant in value but unsafe to hoist (e.g. loads, stores, calls)
    are correctly excluded from the invariant set, so subsequent
    transitive classification of dependent instructions does not
    falsely propagate through them. This yields a smaller-but-correct
    invariant set rather than a larger-but-overaggressive one.

    A safety bound of 50 iterations is enforced to prevent worst-case
    pathological CFGs from running unbounded. In practice convergence
    occurs within a handful of iterations because the dependency
    chain depth among invariant instructions is bounded by the
    longest pure-arithmetic chain inside the loop, which is typically
    very small.

    Returns the number of invariant instructions found. The total
    iteration count is folded into the context's iteration_count
    counter (offset 88) for statistics reporting.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Outer loop terminates when changed == 0 or iteration >= 50.
    Inner walks:
      - For each block id in body_blocks (raw integer Set elements):
        - For each instruction inst in the block:
          - Skip if already in invariant_set (raw instruction-pointer
            membership).
          - Query can_hoist_instruction FIRST (cheap whitelist plus
            exit-dominance; rejects stores, loads, calls, div/mod,
            terminators, and phis before any operand analysis).
          - Enumerate EVERY value use of the instruction through the
            canonical CFG.get_instruction_used_values (header operand
            slots plus phi incomings) and require
            is_loop_invariant_operand to accept each one.
          - On full acceptance: add the instruction POINTER to
            invariant_set, append it to invariant_list (marking order
            is dependency order - an instruction is only marked after
            its operands are classified), set changed = 1.
    After convergence, write the invariant count into loop_info offset
    56 and accumulate the iteration count into context offset 88.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(K * |body| * inst-per-block) per iteration where K is the
    number of iterations until convergence (typically 2-5). The
    inner cost is dominated by can_hoist_instruction (one Set.to_list
    per candidate) and is_loop_invariant_operand (one O(1) omap probe
    per use). Set.contains on the instruction pointer is the warmest
    pure-bookkeeping cost.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let invariant_set be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 16
    Let dominance_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48
    Let def_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 64
    Let invariant_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72
    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16

    Note: The body block-id set does not change during the analysis -
    Note: enumerate it once (raw integer elements, caller-owned List)
    Let body_members be proc to_list from Set with body_blocks
    Let body_count be proc length from List with body_members

    Let iteration be 0
    Let max_iterations be 50
    Let changed be 1

    While changed is equal to 1 and iteration is less than max_iterations:
        Set changed to 0
        Set iteration to iteration plus 1

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than body_count:
            Let block_id be proc get from List with body_members, i

            Let block_ptr be proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id
            If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_list be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block_ptr
                If inst_list is not equal to 0:
                    Let inst_count be proc length from List with inst_list
                    Let j be 0

                    While j is less than inst_count:
                        Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with inst_list, j

                        Note: Check if already marked invariant
                        Let already_invariant be 1
                        If inst_ptr is not equal to 0:
                            Set already_invariant to proc contains from Set with invariant_set, inst_ptr
                        End If

                        If already_invariant is equal to 0:
                            Note: Cheap safety gate first (whitelist +
                            Note: exit dominance)
                            Let can_hoist be proc can_hoist_instruction with inst_ptr, loop_info, dominance_ptr, cfg_ptr

                            If can_hoist is equal to 1:
                                Note: Every value USE must be invariant
                                Note: (canonical enumeration: header
                                Note: operand slots + phi incomings)
                                Let used_values be proc get_instruction_used_values from CFG with inst_ptr
                                Let all_invariant be 1
                                If used_values is not equal to 0:
                                    Let use_count be proc length from List with used_values
                                    Let u_idx be 0
                                    While u_idx is less than use_count:
                                        Let use_id be proc get from List with used_values, u_idx
                                        If use_id is not equal to 0:
                                            Let use_invariant be proc is_loop_invariant_operand with use_id, loop_info, invariant_set, def_map
                                            If use_invariant is equal to 0:
                                                Set all_invariant to 0
                                                Set u_idx to use_count
                                            End If
                                        End If
                                        Set u_idx to u_idx plus 1
                                    End While
                                    proc destroy from List with used_values
                                End If

                                If all_invariant is equal to 1:
                                    Note: Mark as invariant (pointer-keyed
                                    Note: set + marking-order list)
                                    proc add from Set with invariant_set, inst_ptr
                                    proc append from List with invariant_list, inst_ptr
                                    Set changed to 1
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If

                        Set j to j plus 1
                    End While
                End If
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End While

    proc destroy from List with body_members

    Let invariant_count be proc size from Set with invariant_set

    Note: Update loop info
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 56, invariant_count

    Note: Update context iteration count
    Let total_iterations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 88
    Set total_iterations to total_iterations plus iteration
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 88, total_iterations

    Return invariant_count
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HOISTING TRANSFORMATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "hoist_instruction" that takes inst_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Executes the actual CFG mutation that relocates a single invariant
    instruction from its original block (inside the loop body) to the
    loop's preheader. By the time this routine runs the instruction
    has already been certified by can_hoist_instruction, so no safety
    re-validation is needed here; this routine's only responsibility
    is the structural transplant.

    The hoisted instruction is appended to the preheader before the
    preheader's terminating branch — placement at the end of the
    preheader (rather than the beginning) preserves the relative
    order of multiple hoisted instructions when they have
    inter-dependencies, since the fixed-point analysis enumerated
    them in dependency order.

    SSA form is preserved because the preheader strictly dominates
    every block in the loop body (by construction of insert_preheader),
    so every use of the hoisted instruction's defined value, which
    must lie in the body to have been visible to the analysis, remains
    dominated by the new definition site. No phi insertion or
    renaming is required.

    Returns 1 on success, 0 if any argument is null, the loop has no
    preheader (insertion was skipped), or the preheader cannot be
    resolved. A failure here is non-fatal for the pass: the
    instruction remains in its original block and the program is
    still correct, only unoptimised.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Resolve preheader_id from loop_info offset 8. If zero, abort
       with diagnostic (no preheader was inserted for this loop).
    2. Resolve preheader_block via get_block_by_id; abort on failure.
    3. Resolve the original block from the instruction's parent_block
       back-pointer and detach the instruction through the canonical
       CFG.remove_instruction_from_block (removes the List entry,
       re-syncs the cached count, clears parent_block). A failed
       detach ABORTS the hoist — appending a still-resident
       instruction to a second block would double-own it.
    4. Insert the instruction into the preheader BEFORE its jump
       terminator: when the preheader's last instruction is a
       terminator (MIR.is_terminator) the instruction is List-inserted
       at count-1 with the cached count and parent_block stamped
       manually (mirroring the canonical add path); otherwise it is
       appended via CFG.add_instruction_to_block. Successive hoists
       therefore stack in marking order ahead of the terminator,
       preserving dependency order between hoisted instructions.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope
    Hoisting is the irreversible mutation step. The safety predicate
    can_hoist_instruction is the only guard. This routine MUST be
    called only with instructions certified by that predicate;
    invoking it on an arbitrary instruction would violate program
    semantics. The single call site inside hoist_invariant_instructions
    enforces this discipline.
    @End Security_Scope

    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let preheader_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 8
    If preheader_id is equal to 0:
        Display "hoist_instruction: no preheader for loop"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let preheader_block be proc get_block_by_id from CFG with cfg_ptr, preheader_id
    If preheader_block is equal to 0:
        Display "hoist_instruction: preheader block not found"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Detach from the original block (resolved via the parent_block
    Note: back-pointer). A failed detach aborts - the instruction must
    Note: never be resident in two blocks at once.
    Let original_block be proc get_mir_node_parent_block from MIR with inst_ptr
    If original_block is equal to 0:
        Display "hoist_instruction: instruction has no resident block"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let removal_result be proc remove_instruction_from_block from CFG with original_block, inst_ptr
    If removal_result is equal to 0:
        Display "hoist_instruction: failed to detach instruction from original block"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Insert into the preheader BEFORE its jump terminator
    Let preheader_insts be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with preheader_block
    Let preheader_count be proc length from List with preheader_insts

    Let inserted_before_terminator be 0
    If preheader_count is greater than 0:
        Let last_inst be proc get from List with preheader_insts, (preheader_count minus 1)
        Let last_is_terminator be proc is_terminator from MIR with last_inst
        If last_is_terminator is equal to 1:
            proc insert from List with preheader_insts, (preheader_count minus 1), inst_ptr
            Let new_len be proc length from List with preheader_insts
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with preheader_block, 24, new_len
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 56, preheader_block
            Set inserted_before_terminator to 1
        End If
    End If

    If inserted_before_terminator is equal to 0:
        Let add_result be proc add_instruction_to_block from CFG with preheader_block, inst_ptr
        If add_result is equal to 0:
            Display "hoist_instruction: failed to add instruction to preheader"
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "hoist_invariant_instructions" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Iterates the context's invariant_set and relocates every member
    instruction to the supplied loop's preheader via hoist_instruction.
    This routine is the integration point between the analysis phase
    (mark_invariant_instructions, which only mutates the bookkeeping
    set) and the transformation phase (hoist_instruction, which
    mutates the CFG).

    The invariant bookkeeping (set + marking-order list) is PER LOOP:
    optimize_function_with_licm recreates both before each
    mark/hoist pair, so this routine always sees exactly the current
    loop's classification and can never re-hoist a previous loop's
    instructions into the wrong preheader.

    Returns the number of instructions successfully hoisted. The
    return value contributes to the context's hoisted_count statistic.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Iterates the context's invariant_list (offset 72) - NOT the set -
    because the list preserves MARKING ORDER, which is a valid
    dependency (topological) order: an instruction is only marked after
    every operand it uses is classified invariant, so hoisting in list
    order places defining instructions ahead of their users in the
    preheader. Calls hoist_instruction per entry and counts successful
    hoists (return == 1).
    @End Implementation

    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let invariant_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72

    Let hoisted be 0

    Let invariant_count be proc length from List with invariant_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than invariant_count:
        Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with invariant_list, i

        Note: Hoist instruction
        Let result be proc hoist_instruction with inst_ptr, loop_info, cfg_ptr
        If result is equal to 1:
            Set hoisted to hoisted plus 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return hoisted
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ENTRY POINTS AND PIPELINE INTEGRATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "optimize_function_with_licm" that takes function_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Top-level driver for the Loop-Invariant Code Motion optimization
    pass on a single MIRFunction. The pipeline composes the LICM
    stages in their required order:

      1. Construct the LICM context. This derives the CFG, computes
         dominance, builds the local definition map, and allocates
         the bookkeeping structures.
      2. Detect natural loops. Without any loops the pass terminates
         successfully (no work to do).
      3. Insert preheaders so every loop has a single landing pad for
         hoisted instructions, then recompute dominance against the
         mutated topology.
      4. Sort loops inner-first (ascending body size).
      5. For each loop, with FRESH per-loop invariant bookkeeping,
         run mark_invariant_instructions to find the transitive
         closure of safe-to-hoist instructions, then
         hoist_invariant_instructions to materialise the transform.
         The two are tightly coupled: marking must finish before
         hoisting because hoisting mutates the CFG and would
         invalidate the analysis if interleaved.
      6. Destroy the context.

    The pass is idempotent at the function level: re-running LICM on
    a function that has no further invariant motion to perform
    produces no new motion (already-hoisted instructions reside in
    preheaders outside every loop body).

    Returns 1 on success (including the "no loops found" case), 0 on
    context creation failure or null function.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Stage 1: create_licm_context(function). On null return, propagate 0.
    Stage 2: detect_natural_loops. On 0 return, destroy context and
    return 1 (success with no work).
    Stage 3: insert_preheaders (owns the dominance recompute).
    Stage 4: sort_loops_by_body_size on loops_list (offset 8).
    Stage 5: iterate loops_list; for each LoopInfo, recreate the
    invariant set (offset 16) and marking-order list (offset 72), call
    mark_invariant_instructions and hoist_invariant_instructions,
    accumulate hoisted count, increment loops_processed counter at
    context offset 32.
    Final: write total_hoisted into context offset 24, destroy
    context, return 1. Statistics remain queryable via
    print_licm_stats before destruction when a caller orchestrates
    the stages manually.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Per-function cost is dominated by stage 1 (dominance + definition
    map construction) and the fixed-point analysis in stage 5. For
    functions with no loops the early exit after stage 2 keeps the
    cost at one dominance computation plus one CFG scan, which is
    why the heuristic guard in should_run_licm matters for compile
    time on loop-light input.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If function_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "optimize_function_with_licm: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 1: Create context (derives the CFG, computes dominance,
    Note: builds the local definition map)
    Let context_ptr be proc create_licm_context with function_ptr
    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 2: Detect natural loops
    Let loop_count be proc detect_natural_loops with context_ptr

    If loop_count is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_licm_context with context_ptr
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Step 3: Insert preheaders (recomputes dominance afterwards)
    proc insert_preheaders with context_ptr

    Note: Step 3.5: Order loops inner-first (ascending body size) so an
    Note: inner loop's hoists land in its own preheader before the
    Note: enclosing loop is analyzed
    Let loops_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8
    proc sort_loops_by_body_size with loops_list

    Note: Step 4: Process each loop with FRESH per-loop invariant
    Note: bookkeeping - reusing the set across loops would re-hoist a
    Note: previous loop's instructions into the current loop's preheader
    Let total_hoisted be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than loop_count:
        Let loop_info be proc get from List with loops_list, i

        Note: Reset per-loop invariant set and marking-order list
        Let old_set be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 16
        If old_set is not equal to 0:
            proc destroy from Set with old_set
        End If
        Let fresh_set be proc create from Set
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 16, fresh_set

        Let old_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72
        If old_list is not equal to 0:
            proc destroy from List with old_list
        End If
        Let fresh_list be proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72, fresh_list

        Note: Mark invariant instructions
        proc mark_invariant_instructions with context_ptr, loop_info

        Note: Hoist invariant instructions
        Let hoisted be proc hoist_invariant_instructions with context_ptr, loop_info
        Set total_hoisted to total_hoisted plus hoisted

        Note: Update loops processed counter
        Let loops_processed be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32
        Set loops_processed to loops_processed plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32, loops_processed

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Update total hoisted count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24, total_hoisted

    Note: Step 5: Destroy context
    proc destroy_licm_context with context_ptr

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "sort_loops_by_body_size" that takes loops_list as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Orders detected loops by ascending body-block count, which places
    inner loops (strict subsets of their enclosing loops, hence smaller
    bodies) before outer ones. Processing inner loops first is the
    standard LICM schedule: an inner hoist lands in the inner preheader
    (which is inside the outer loop body), keeping each instruction's
    motion minimal and sound; the outer pass then operates on the
    already-optimized inner structure. A simple in-place selection sort
    is used - loop counts per function are tiny (rarely above single
    digits), so asymptotics are irrelevant and the sort allocates
    nothing.
    @End Reasoning

    If loops_list is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc length from List with loops_list
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let min_idx be i
        Let min_loop be proc get from List with loops_list, min_idx
        Let min_body be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with min_loop, 16
        Let min_size be proc size from Set with min_body

        Let j be i plus 1
        While j is less than count:
            Let cand_loop be proc get from List with loops_list, j
            Let cand_body be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cand_loop, 16
            Let cand_size be proc size from Set with cand_body
            If cand_size is less than min_size:
                Set min_idx to j
                Set min_size to cand_size
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        If min_idx is not equal to i:
            Let tmp be proc get from List with loops_list, i
            Let min_entry be proc get from List with loops_list, min_idx
            proc set from List with loops_list, i, min_entry
            proc set from List with loops_list, min_idx, tmp
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "run_licm_pass" that takes function_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convenience wrapper for running LICM as an optimization pass. Takes
    the MIRFunction pointer (the pass needs the function for value-id
    allocation and definition lookups; the CFG is derived internally).

    Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure.
    @End Reasoning

    Return proc optimize_function_with_licm with function_ptr
End Process

Process called "should_run_licm" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Cheap pre-pass profitability guard. Returns 0 (skip LICM) when
    the function is so small that the dominance-computation cost of
    running LICM exceeds any plausible speedup from invariant motion.
    A function with fewer than three basic blocks cannot contain a
    non-trivial natural loop (a loop requires at minimum a header, a
    body block, and a back-edge source — even a self-loop needs an
    entry block to dominate it), so skipping such functions is sound
    and avoids paying the dominance construction cost.

    The actual back-edge presence check is performed inside
    detect_natural_loops; this guard is purely a block-count
    heuristic intended to keep compile-time overhead near zero on
    loop-light input.

    Returns 1 when LICM should run, 0 to skip.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads the canonical CFG.get_cfg_block_count. Returns 0 immediately
    on null CFG or block_count < 3. Otherwise returns 1.
    @End Implementation

    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get block count
    Let block_count be proc get_cfg_block_count from CFG with cfg_ptr

    Note: Skip trivial functions
    If block_count is less than 3:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Should run on non-trivial functions
    Note: (Actual loop detection happens in optimization pass)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "get_licm_pass_name" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the name of this optimization pass.
    @End Reasoning

    Return "Loop-Invariant Code Motion"
End Process

Process called "get_licm_pass_description" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a description of this optimization pass.
    @End Reasoning

    Return "Hoists loop-invariant computations out of loops using fixed-point analysis"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: END OF LICM IMPLEMENTATION
Note: ============================================================================
